ğŸ” Cause: Application errors, missing configurations, or resources.
ğŸ”§ Resolution: Check pod logs using kubectl logs [pod-name] to identify the error. Ensure configurations are correct and resources (like memory and CPU) are properly allocated.

âš ï¸ Issue: Persistent Volume Claims (PVC) Stuck in Pending State
ğŸ” Cause: Insufficient storage or misconfigured StorageClass.
ğŸ”§ Resolution: Verify storage availability and ensure the StorageClass is correctly defined. Use kubectl describe pvc [pvc-name] for detailed error messages.

â— Issue: Service Unreachable
ğŸ” Cause: Incorrect service configuration or network policies.
ğŸ”§ Resolution: Check the service and endpoint details with kubectl describe svc [service-name]. Ensure network policies allow traffic to the service.

â³ Issue: High Pod Startup Latency
ğŸ” Cause: Resource constraints or node performance issues.
ğŸ”§ Resolution: Review resource requests and limits for pods. Consider increasing node resources or scaling the cluster.

ğŸ”„ Issue: Rolling Update Failures
ğŸ” Cause: Incompatible application versions or insufficient replicas.
ğŸ”§ Resolution: Ensure backward compatibility of new versions. Increase the number of replicas to maintain availability during updates.

ğŸ” Issue: Node Not Ready
ğŸ” Cause: Node resource exhaustion, network issues, or kubelet failure.
ğŸ”§ Resolution: Check node status with kubectl describe node [node-name]. Investigate kubelet logs and ensure node resources are sufficient.

ğŸ”§ Issue: Container Image Pull Errors
ğŸ” Cause: Incorrect image name, tag, or registry authentication issues.
ğŸ”§ Resolution: Verify the image name and tag. Ensure credentials for private registries are configured correctly in Kubernetes secrets.

ğŸ“Š Issue: Metrics Server Not Working
ğŸ” Cause: Incorrect installation or configuration.
